{"dataset":"articles","provider":"pursuit","banner_url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/Design-for-all-life-_62e22619-4396-46ac-a871-8d9728fb53e1.jpg","id":"76347","text":"<div class=\"container\"><span><p>Have you ever dreamed of having your own <a href=\"https://iview.abc.net.au/show/grand-designs\" target=\"_blank\">Grand Designs</a> moment? An opportunity to live in a space designed for you, perfectly fitting your lifestyle, needs and daily routines.</p><p>Today, a growing number of designers are working to help other creatures that live next to humans enjoy these comforts too.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/76355/Design-for-all-life-_62e22619-4396-46ac-a871-8d9728fb53e1.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Left: Bricks for birds by Feral Partnerships, exhibited at San Mei Gallery, London (2022). Picture: Matthew Darmour-Paul. Right: A bee and insect hotel at The System Garden, University of Melbourne. Picture: Kylie Soanes </figcaption></figure></div><span><p>Traditional design prioritises efficiency, uniformity and consumption, but often sacrifices the richness and nuance of living communities. The resulting structures are often equally hostile to human and non-human beings.</p><p>But, by considering the lives and needs of plants, animals and even microbes, we have an opportunity to design more sustainable, equitable and innovative spaces that benefit all forms of life.</p><p>If you would like to have a say in the design of your own dwelling, then so should crabs or owls. They are experts in their own lives and their choices should lead design.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0032/79871/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Environment</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/new-design-tech-offers-hope-for-urban-wildlife?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>New design tech offers hope for urban wildlife <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>However, design collaboration with non-humans is a tricky affair.</p><p>Animals and plants don’t read project briefs, often live secretive lives and don’t welcome surveillance or intrusions. And yet, with careful observation, data interpretation and testing in the field – we can make significant progress.</p><p>For example, at the <a href=\"https://wiki.deepdesignlab.online/\" target=\"_blank\">Deep Design Lab</a>, we’re on a mission to transform the way humans approach design by shifting towards a ‘more-than-human’ perspective.</p><p>Our projects range from eco-friendly <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1111/2041-210X.13806\" target=\"_self\">habitat structures</a> inspired by termite nests to <a href=\"https://vimeo.com/568783734\" target=\"_blank\">smart systems that reduce light pollution</a> and tools for preserving <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1186/s43238-020-00003-9\" target=\"_blank\">more-than-human heritage</a> like those created by <a href=\"https://www.academia.edu/50762547/Respect_for_Old_Age_and_Dignity_in_Death_The_Case_of_Urban_Trees\" target=\"_blank\">large old trees</a>.</p><p>Thankfully, we’re not alone in the mission to advocate for non-human life.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/76351/Design-for-all-life-_87db853f-d70b-4e3d-bb84-50f95a8da259.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Attitudes toward non-human life in design and management. The range is from the anthropocentric attitudes on the left to the ecocentric attitudes on the right. The white text highlights examples of design practices. The deep green region on the right is most important but today the shallow approaches are much more common. Picture: Deep Design Lab </figcaption></figure></div><span><p>In a recent issue of <a href=\"https://www.architecture.com.au/vic-chapter/architect-victoria-design-for-all-life-architecture-and-planning\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"italics\">Architect Victoria</a>, we gathered leading experts in “Design for All Life”. Here are some great examples that aim to address the needs of more-than-human clients.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">Bird-friendly windows</h2></span><span><p>Those gorgeous floor-to-ceiling windows may provide beautiful views for human dwellers but can be deadly for our feathered friends. In North America alone, close to <a href=\"https://www.dezeen.com/2022/03/09/glass-collisions-bird-deaths/#:~:text=Collisions with buildings cause billions,third of these are fatal.\" target=\"_blank\">one billion birds</a> die by colliding with windows each year.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0023/97043/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Environment</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/making-cities-work-for-every-urban-dweller?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Making cities work for every urban dweller <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>By considering how birds visualise and react to reflective surfaces, we can design environments that better suit their needs.</p><p>Simple <a href=\"https://issuu.com/architecture-chapter/docs/av_edition_3_2022/40\" target=\"_blank\">strings across the glass</a> often work, but some architects, designers, city planners, and legislators are going further and creating exquisitely patterned <a href=\"https://theiwrc.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/BirdFriendlyBuildingDesign1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">façade structures</a> that wrap entire buildings.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">Walls for wildlife</h2></span><span><p>More-than-human design approaches can help make better use of ‘wasted’ space. A humble <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2021/may/18/securing-their-swift-return-how-a-simple-brick-can-help-migratory-birds-aoe\" target=\"_blank\">brick wall</a> can become a wildlife haven in the right circumstances.</p><p>For example, custom-made blocks allow many birds to nest in the walls of houses. The design suits the nesting needs of the species and the materials ensure that housing insulation is not compromised.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/76357/Design-for-all-life-_74bf94d3-ef14-413d-8ac1-bdd5039a4c53.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>A window with strings visible to birds in Escarpment House, by Virginia Kerridge Architect. Picture: Matthew Darmour-Paul </figcaption></figure></div><span><p>Closer to home, the University of Melbourne’s own <a href=\"https://sustainablecampus.unimelb.edu.au/biodiversity/insect-hotel\" target=\"_blank\">pollinator hotel</a> fits into a disused doorway to create a habitat for native bees.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">Bespoke tree hollows</h2></span><span><p><a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/new-design-tech-offers-hope-for-urban-wildlife\" target=\"_blank\">Custom homes</a> can also help birds and mammals that live in tree hollows. The Deep Design Lab will soon have a website that can help you to customise a tree-hollow design that suits your local environment.</p><p>The <a href=\"https://issuu.com/architecture-chapter/docs/av_edition_3_2022/50\" target=\"_blank\">website</a> enables you to order a 3D-printed hollow or make the hollow yourself using novel materials like earth and mycelium (the root-like structures of mushrooms).</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/76354/Design-for-all-life-_947bac8b-ba2f-4b39-a7ae-eb138d09d455.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>A custom-built bird nest made of earth in northern Italy. Pictures: Deep Design Lab</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>These do-it-yourself approaches make it possible for residents and community groups to install computer-designed hollows in backyards and parks.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">Underwater gardens</h2></span><span><p>Our urban waterways often have hard edges. Smooth, concrete seawalls and expansive marinas do not provide the nooks and crannies that aquatic organisms need to survive.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/83166/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Environment</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/designing-in-difference?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Designing-in difference <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>The <a href=\"https://www.livingseawalls.com.au/\" target=\"_blank\">Living Seawalls</a> project combines cutting-edge design and the science of ecology to create complex artificial habitats that mimic rocky reefs and seaweed forests for crabs and worms.</p><p>The seawall panels in Sydney Harbour support at least 36 per cent more species than plain, unmodified seawalls, with as many as 85 species of invertebrates, seaweeds and fish.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">Probiotic buildings</h2></span><span><p>Even the tiniest living organisms can benefit from more-than-human design approaches. Building materials that have <a href=\"https://doi-org.ezproxy.une.edu.au/10.1080/13602365.2021.1880822\" target=\"_blank\">pores and textures</a> can host more microbes in cities.</p><p>Rather than trying to eliminate microorganisms from our living spaces, we can <a href=\"https://issuu.com/architecture-chapter/docs/av_edition_3_2022/62\" target=\"_blank\">embrace</a> beneficial bacteria that can help us <a href=\"https://www.hachettebookgroup.com/titles/rob-dunn/never-home-alone/9781541645745/?lens=basic-books\" target=\"_blank\">maintain healthy biomes</a> on our skin and in our guts.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/76356/Design-for-all-life-_02a5caf4-c9b8-403f-8c06-64f42bb6dd7a.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Probiotic ceramic tiles embedded with a soil derived microbe that can inhibit harmful bacteria. Left: Microscale image of porous ceramic material. Right: Geometrical surface details of probiotic pores with porous and non-porous zones. Picture: Richard Beckett </figcaption></figure></div><span><h2 class=\"center\">Towards design for all life</h2></span><span><p>There’s a growing interdisciplinary effort to address issues that extend beyond human needs.</p><p>The popularity of <a href=\"https://www.independent.co.uk/tv/lifestyle/tiktok-australia-tree-frog-house-b2291258.html\" target=\"_blank\">3D-printed frog hotels</a> or <a href=\"https://twitter.com/HumphreyJE_/status/1634368345062641665\" target=\"_blank\">DIY possum palaces</a> tells us there’s a broader social appetite for living with nature. But this is about much more than building high-tech homes for animals.</p><p>Advocates argue that the practice of designing for all life can enable deeper consideration of <a href=\"https://issuu.com/architecture-chapter/docs/av_edition_3_2022/68\" target=\"_blank\">Connection to Country principles</a>, more biodiverse and animal-friendly cities, and better outcomes for human health.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/83670/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Environment</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/designing-liveable-cities-for-our-future-climate?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Designing liveable cities for our future climate <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>All of this would help us move toward more ethical and sustainable architecture.</p><p>Such architecture should highlight the value of biodiversity, the interconnectedness of ecosystems – as well as the impact of human actions.</p><p>Greater collaboration with the non-human beings that live along with us can help us reconsider where and how we live, creating a more <a href=\"https://issuu.com/architecture-chapter/docs/av_edition_3_2022/74\" target=\"_blank\">just</a> and sustainable world for all.</p><p><span class=\"italics\">You can read more about these topics in the open-access special issue of</span> <a href=\"https://www.architecture.com.au/vic-chapter/architect-victoria-design-for-all-life-architecture-and-planning\" target=\"_blank\">Architect Victoria</a><span class=\"italics\">, a journal of the Australian Institute of Architects.</span></p><p>Banner: A sparrow flies out of a facade nest in Munich, by <a href=\"https://animal-aided-design.de/en/\" target=\"_blank\">Studio Animal-Aided Design</a>/Samuel Inter</p></span></div>\n<p>This article was first published on <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\">Pursuit</a>. <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/design-for-all-life\">Read the original article.</a></p>","date_published":"2023-04-24T13:05:14+10:00","date_updated":"2023-04-24T13:05:14+10:00","url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/design-for-all-life","title":"Design for (all) life","summary":"Humans create most designs for themselves, but can and should use opportunities to make spaces that benefit all forms of life","org_objects":[],"tag_objects":[],"author_objects":[{"name":"Dr Stanislav Roudavski","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/dr-stanislav-roudavski","orcid":"","fae_url":"https://findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/profile/204177-stanislav-roudavski","email":""},{"name":"Dr Kylie Soanes","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/dr-kylie-soanes","orcid":"","fae_url":"https://findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/display/person176188","email":""},{"name":"Dan Parker","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/dan-parker","orcid":"","fae_url":"","email":""}],"citation_objects":[{"credentials":"Dr Stanislav Roudavski"},{"credentials":"Dr Kylie Soanes"},{"credentials":"Dan Parker"}]}